[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Prime is an Oregon-year-old female from New Castle, who was recently hospitalized for anemia and a suspected GI bleed on April 9, 2010.  Approximately six-months earlier, she had undergone some type of colon evaluation including a barium enema.  A lot of the history is gathered from Mrs. Prime, but she has either vascular or Alzheimer's-type dementia, and has an activated power of attorney who is her son, Nbtmkix Jkoy, and a lot of the history is gathered through her family.  This included her son who is the POA, as well as her other son whom she lives with, Dqyx Eizu, and her daughter.  Apparently, she underwent a barium enema for colon evaluation as in 2005 on her last colonoscopy it was recommended she undergo a follow-up colon evaluation.  From the family's report, no one was concerned about the findings on the barium enema at-home.  I think it revealed diverticulosis in reviewing her outside records (a review by providers of the study), but there was nothing concerning that the family was aware of regarding the test.  She then came in for a routine follow-up on April 8, 2010, to Dr. Carrell with complaints of weakness and fatigue.  Blood work was obtained after she left the clinic that night, and her hemoglobin was 7.3.  She then went to the hospital at the request of Dr. Carrell and as part of her evaluation for GI bleeding underwent a colonoscopy on April 12, 2010.  This revealed a-1-cm polyp immediately adjacent to the appendiceal orifice which was removed with pathology reviewed here and consistent with a tubular adenoma with low-grade dysplasia.  Several centimeters distal to the ileocecal valve a mass was noted in the right colon.  This was photographed and biopsied, but not tattooed.  It is not mentioned exactly how large this was, although it seemed to occupy at least one-third of the circumference of the colon and was non-obstructing.  Pathology reviewed here reveals invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma with signet ring cell features associated with a tubulovillous adenoma. There was no evidence of diverticulitis.  She had pandiverticulosis, moderate in the sigmoid colon..
She also had an upper EGD at that time which revealed a hiatal hernia and several areas of hyperemia suggestive of possible minimal gastritis or superficial erosions.  Biopsy performed locally revealed this was negative for H. pylori.  Here the pathology slides were consistent with intestinal metaplasia.  She had three blood transfusions, and on April 15 before discharge her hemoglobin was 11.8.  She met with a surgeon in the hospital, but she and her family did not feel comfortable with this surgeon, and therefore, they are here for another opinion.
Interestingly, Mrs. Prime has a prior history of colon cancer in 1968.  In reviewing her records and in discussing with her, it is thought that maybe this was actually a cecal cancer.  However, on her colonoscopy on the 12th, it was pretty clear that the cecum was "clearly identified with visualization of the ileocecal valve", making it unlikely that she actually had a cecal resection or right hemicolectomy previously.  She apparently had a colostomy temporarily after the surgery which was subsequently taken down.  She did not receive adjuvant treatment and has no other family history of colorectal cancer.  She used to move her bowels once-a-day, but now it is about once every-other-day.  She has not had abdominal bloating.  She denies abdominal pain.  She has some fecal incontinence which has been going on a couple years, and she wears Depends.  At times she can make it to the bathroom.  She has not noticed bright-red blood per rectum.  She had not really had other symptoms except for the profound anemia with associated weakness and fatigue.  She denies recent abdominal pain or significant weight-loss.  Her appetite had been stable.  Her family reports that she had been in a pretty good state of health for the last six-months up until her recent hospitalization.  She currently resides with her son, Dqyx Eizu, as she is widowed.  They feel they have been managing things well with this living arrangement, although she has been a lot weaker since getting out of the hospital.  She was just discharged on the 14th and had a follow-up in the office on the 15th of April.  Her Aggrenox, which she had been on for a history of cerebrovascular disease and carotid stenosis, has been held since her hospitalization and her 325 of aspirin which she generally takes.  A CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis was obtained locally on April 14th.  We do not yet have those images here to review, but per local review, this revealed a-1.5-cm polypoid filling defect in the lateral wall of the descending colon.  I am wondering if this is a typo, but in this final report supposedly of her CT-scan of the abdomen and pelvis, the descending colon is mentioned twice, although it is mentioned she had polypoid thickening along the lateral wall of the proximal descending colon measuring approximately 1.5-cm in diameter just distal to the ileocecal valve so I am wondering if this is meant to be ascending, but there are two aspects in this report where it is mentioned as descending.  She also had six low-attenuation lesions seen throughout the liver with the largest being 2.4-cm that are suspected to be consistent with cysts.  She had cholelithiasis.  She has never had gallbladder symptoms.  She did not have a CEA done locally.
In reviewing Mrs. Prime's outside records and hospitalization, it was mentioned she was a DNR.  I brought this up with the patient and the family to clarify whether this is the case or what the goals of her care are at this time.  After a 20-minute discussion regarding code status, the patient and the family tell me they did not understand what the DNR meant and did not feel that they made this decision specifically while she was in the hospital, and they would like her to be a full code.  At this point it is uncertain whether she has a terminal illness, and therefore, they are comfortable and want to proceed with evaluation for possible surgery for her cancer and then decide based on the risks versus benefits with her other comorbidities whether this would be appropriate and consider her quality of life.
Mrs. Prime was seen here in 2007 in Neurology and diagnosed with dementia compatible with either multi-infarct dementia or Alzheimer's disease.  Her sons report they have been activated as her powers of attorney for approximately three years.  Although she is still able to do a lot of things on her own as far as certain ADLs and make certain decision, the large decisions are made by her power of attorney, her son, Nbtmkix Jkoy, and then Dqyx Eizu, her other son, is the secondary power of attorney who lives with her.  She had been doing quite well and generally was fairly independent with her ADLs up until her recent hospitalization.  Since her recent hospitalization, she has needed more assistance.  She uses a walker to ambulate, and she is able to walk about 30 steps.  She cannot traverse stairs well, although with the help of her son and a railing, she is able to go up the four to five stairs into their home.  She has not had recent falls.  The family is under the impression that she will likely need to be placed in a skilled nursing facility following surgery if this ends up having surgery.  She has been a lot weaker since she got out of the hospital.  She needs assistance making meals, housekeeping, and with toileting.  She is able to dress herself generally per her son's report.  She can feed herself.  She also can bathe herself, and they have a shower chair in the home at this time.  Her son manages her medications for her.

