3.  Depression with anxiety.  She has been on sertraline for approximately a year-and-a-half to two years.  She informs me today her mood is stable.  She denies suicidal ideation.  Her family also thinks she is stable in regard to this, although, of course, she is concerned about the news of malignancy.
4.  Hyperlipidemia.  No recent changes to medication.
5.  Coronary artery disease.  She is status-post three-vessel CABG here in 1995.  She then subsequently had a non-Q-wave MI in 2001.  An angiogram at that time in March 2001 revealed that her bypass grafts were patent, and the right middle coronary artery was 100% occluded, the proximal right coronary artery was 30% occluded, the first obtuse marginal branch was 70% obstructed, the distal circumflex was 40% obstructed, the proximal circumflex was 70% obstructed, the middle left anterior descending was 100% occluded, proximal left anterior descending was 50% obstructed, and the left main coronary artery was 60% obstructed.  It does not appear intervention was performed at that time.  Her last echocardiogram in our records was from March 2005 which revealed an ejection fraction of 65% with grade 2/4 left ventricular diastolic dysfunction with moderately elevated left ventricular filling pressures.  She had normal left ventricular size and no regional wall motion abnormalities.  She had moderate mitral valve regurg, a patent foramen ovale, and mild pulmonary hypertension.  She reports not having a recent cardiac evaluation.  She did use nitroglycerin two-months ago for chest pain that radiated to the left-side.
